<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-809-314  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 809 314.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>High Technology Business  Nov-Dec 1989 v9 n9 p38(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Voice recognition becoming feasible. (Newsletter Digest)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In voice recognition, the human voice is digitized and matchedagainst coded dictionaries for word identification.andP;  Mostavailable speech-recognition systems can only identify clearlyspoken, isolated words; enabling a computer to understand natural,flowing speech is the goal.andP;  Two major problems with continuousspeech recognition are acoustics and language properties.andP;  Largevoice-recognition systems are already being used in the medicalfield.andP;  Toshiba is developing voice-activated ticket dispensersfor commuter trains and Sears, Roebuck and Co may be offeringvoice-activated car controls.andP;  Dragon Systems Inc'sDragonDictate-30K has the largest vocabulary, it can recognize30,000 words.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Artificial intelligenceDigitized VoiceVoice RecognitionFuture TechnologiesNatural Language Interfaces.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>